doctemplate (1.3-0ubuntu0ppa11) karmic; urgency=low

  * This release contains many changes in the following areas:
    - Standard approach to customization: docbook, fop and html customization 
      param files and xsl (for overring standard templates). Note that the 
      *PARAM files mentioned in the previous log entry are moved (with other 
      files) to lib/<type>-customization/, and COMMONPARAMS is renamed to 
      DOCBOOKPARAMS.
    - The lib/html-customizaton and fop-customization dirs implement the 
      "spec file" based approach to titlepage customization. 
    - html generation is now done in two passes: xinclude and docbook.xsl 
      instead of several, which facilitates customization in the 
      usual way (docbook template overrides instead of separate transforms
      to insert html attributes for css)
    - lib/style.css: better design
    - javascript inserted to generated html through standard docbook xsl
      approach and modified to use new override-based html 
    - automatic support for fop hyphenization pattern use if the user
      adds lib/apache/fop-hyph.jar
    - much better pdf layout, with page break after title page, after TOC
      and more
 

 -- Kyle Nitzsche <kyle.nitzsche@canonical.com>  Wed, 13 Jan 2010 12:24:28 -0500

doctemplate (1.3-0ubuntu0ppa10) karmic; urgency=low

  * now there are three user-configurable files for xslt params:
    - COMMONPARAMS: applied to first transform of xml, therefore always 
  applied
    - HTMLPARAMS: only applied with make_html (after COMMON, of course)
    - FOPARAMS: only applied with make_pdf (after COMMON, of course)
  * Much improved make_* command line output
  * move user's style.css to project root, instead of using the one in project's
    lib/style.css, in order to allow a user to customize style.css and not have
    the customizations blown away when they update a project from a new version
    of doctemplate (no user-cutomizable files should be in lib, theoretically)

 -- Kyle Nitzsche <kyle.nitzsche@canonical.com>  Fri, 08 Jan 2010 11:26:58 -0500

